Finding related to probable cause.


The Director shall make a finding related to probable cause, so far as practicable, no later than one hundred eighty (180) days after receipt of the complaint or amended complaint.



At the end of the investigation under this chapter, the Director shall prepare a finding related to probable cause consisting of a final investigative report and recommended order. The Director's finding shall be served upon the complainant and the respondent. The Director's final investigative report and recommended order shall contain:


The names and dates of contacts with witnesses;



A summary and the date of correspondence and other contacts with the complainant and the respondent;



A summary description of other pertinent records;



A summary of witness statements;



Any responses to requests for discovery; and



Recommendations including, but not limited to the issues of liability for a violation of this chapter, affirmative action, reasonable accommodation, quantifiable damages, costs, Attorney's fees, interest and civil fines.




The Director's recommended order shall become final ten (10) days after issuance, unless a hearing is requested pursuant to Section 11A-23(9)(a). The final investigative report and final order may be amended if additional evidence is later discovered and if amended shall become final ten (10) days thereafter.



If the Director determines that no probable cause exists to believe that a violation of this chapter has occurred or is about to occur, the Director shall promptly dismiss the complaint. The Director shall publicly disclose each such dismissal.

At the conclusion of a hearing and upon a finding of public accommodations discrimination, the Board may consider fines without cost to the complainant. The Board may impose the following fines:


Up to then thousand dollars ($10,000.00) if the respondent has not previously been found guilty of a violation of this article;



Up to twenty-five thousand dollars ($25,000.00) if the respondent has been found guilty of one (1) prior violation of this article within the preceding five (5) years prior to filing of a complaint;



Up to fifty thousand dollars ($50,000.00) if the respondent has been found guilty of two (2) or more violations of this article within the preceding seven (7) years prior to filing of a complaint.
